.rgmdl is the extension for the rat game model format but like
nobody really cares so use whatever you want.
it's got a few parts to it: a model, a texture, and a texture
map.
models and textures are denoted with a filepath like so:
model = asdf;
texture = asdf;
whitespace before and after the = operator is trimmed but
everything between the first non-whitespace character and the
semicolon is taken as the file name. no fancy stuff like
globbing and you only get to set it once per model (once per
file). the only supported model files are in STL (as in [2])
and the only supported texture files are in PPM (as in [0])
you can manually assign uv coordinates to triangles using 
texmap=[(x,y),(x,y),(x,y)...]
this will set triangles' uv coordinates in sequence (every 3
points correspond to 1 triangle) but that's a massive pain in
the ass so you can use texmap_filldefault (below)
because manually assigning textures is horrible and evil, in
an rgmdl file you can use a few functions
- texmap_offset(x,y)
    shifts every assigned point on the map by (x,y) where x
    and y are floats.
- texmap_scale(x,y)
    transforms each assigned point by (x0,y0)->(x0*x,y0*y). i
    can't say multiples because there's like 5 products. x and
    y are floats.
- texmap_filldefault(a,b)
    a and b are characters x, y, or z. fills in all unassigned
    points on the texture map with the value of their
    mesh-space counterpart. example: texmap_filldefault(z,x)
    sets all unassigned uv points's x to their counterpart's z
    and their y to their counterpart's x.
-texmap_filldefault()
    assigns texture coordinates automatically. the first point
    on the triangle becomes (0,0), the second becomes (x,0)
    where x is the distance between the first and second, and
    the third becomes (x,y) where distances between the first
    and third and second and third are equivalent across
    coordinate spaces, achieved by plane definitions as a
    function returning distance i think (see [1]). 
whitespace is allowed in a lot of places but also no
guarantees
you can comment, everything after a # before a newline doesn't
get parsed but like it might get messed up if you do it in the
middle of something important
